docs.abstract: The relatively unknown story of photography’s important role in the Chicano movement is featured in a new exhibition at the Autry Museum of the American West.
docs.snippet: The relatively unknown story of photography’s important role in the Chicano movement is featured in a new exhibition at the Autry Museum of the American West.
docs.lead_paragraph: From 1967 to 1977, La Raza, the Los Angeles newspaper turned magazine, provided a vital and dynamic forum for Chicano political and cultural expression. Employing a range of disciplines, including photojournalism, graphic art, satire, poetry and political commentary, it was both chronicler and participant in the Mexican-American struggle for equality and justice.

docs.lead_paragraph: Police officials in Rochester, N.Y., said on Thursday that they had filed departmental charges against an officer who took part in arresting Daniel Prude, a Black man who died in March 2020 after the police pinned him face down on the ground and put a mesh hood over his head.

docs.abstract: Older volunteers are reluctant to work during the pandemic. High school students, who are increasingly politically engaged and have more time, are taking their place.
docs.snippet: Older volunteers are reluctant to work during the pandemic. High school students, who are increasingly politically engaged and have more time, are taking their place.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — During the Wisconsin primary in April, Jacob Major, a high school student, noticed how the line for one of Milwaukee’s five polling locations dragged on for blocks. At the beginning of the pandemic, the city did not have enough volunteers and officials to staff its 180 polling sites, leading it to shutter 175 of them.

headline.main: With Polling Sites Lacking Workers, a New Generation Steps Up
headline.print_headline: With Older Poll Workers Wary, a New Generation Is Stepping In to Help
